But as Case and Deaton continued digging into the data, it became clear that the grim trends didn’t apply only to middle-aged whites.
But over the past three decades, deaths of despair among whites without a college degree — especially those under age 50 — have soared.
The two economists initially focused on non-Hispanic whites because the mortality trends were worst for them.
The combined result is a divergence in the life expectancy of white college graduates and non-graduates.
Students who attend and graduate from college do better in life than otherwise similar students who didn’t get the same opportunities.